Title: cs292j Final Project  
Author: Carleton Miyamoto Mark Stemm 
Date: May 8, 1995  
Abstract: We compare two wireless networking systems designed for mobile hosts, the Internet Engineering Task Force(IETF)'s Mobile IP proposal and the DARPA Packet Radio network. We compare the two systems based on performance and scalability metrics. The scenario used to compare the two systems is based in the city of Berkeley, CA, and involves approximately 100 mobile hosts. Simulation results show the Packet Radio network has lower hop counts at the expense of more handoffs. The fixed network structure of Mobile IP makes it less flexible in utilizing network resources in the presence of congestion and failure, but the network resources are used more effectively in normal operation. Per-device bandwidth is less for the Packet Radio network because wireless links are shared among more devices. Packet Radio network performance also degrades sharply in the presence of poor wireless link quality.
