Reference-contexts: One early system was the DARPA Packet Radio Network [1], which operated as a collection of mobile devices that acted both as end devices and routing nodes. More recently, the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) has proposed an extension to IP, called Mobile IP <ref> [2] </ref>, which is designed to integrate into existing wired networks and provide mobility to devices via endpoint wireless links. This paper presents a comparison of these two systems, with an emphasis on quantifiable metrics. We construct a sample scenario based in Berkeley, CA. with approximately 100 mobile devices.
